02:50.296 --> 02:59.888
Now, a couple of questions now very quickly on you 
concerning personal comments, which you may

02:50.296 --> 02:59.888
choose to ignore, by the way. For example, given 
the way that the problems you see facing this

03:00.475 --> 03:16.476
country, let's say that in terms of nuclear 
energy, with energy being overlapping problems,

03:00.475 --> 03:16.476
what's your attitude towards developing nuclear 
energy and nuclear waste? Do you feel it should be

03:16.516 --> 03:17.757
stopped? Should it be continued? Do you feel as if 
the oceans can serve as sort of a waste deposit?

03:25.687 --> 03:26.008
That's strange. If you had asked me that two months 
ago, I would have said, No problem. Don't worry

03:32.980 --> 03:33.680
about it. But unfortunately, between then and 
now, I read this rather excellent book on We Almost

03:33.900 --> 03:45.611
Lost Detroit is the title of it. And it concerns 
some accidents that we've already had using fast

03:45.651 --> 03:54.879
breeder reactors and water-cooled reactors. And 
my opinion was that we had self-quenching cooling

04:00.533 --> 04:05.097
fluids for use in these reactors. And it was 
impossible for them to get out of hand, because if

04:05.237 --> 04:14.906
the neutron flux got too high, why, the material 
would just become opaque to neutron flux, and it

04:05.237 --> 04:14.906
would shut down. But apparently, this stuff, the 
fusion, the uranium and the thorium don't behave

04:16.047 --> 04:24.876
like they should. And I guess they develop 
hotspots within the core. And once the hot spot

04:30.250 --> 04:37.077
develops, it can do some damage to the cooling 
system, to the flow of it. And then it ceases to be

04:37.798 --> 04:41.962
cooled correctly, and that hot spot continues to 
get hotter. And so now I'm convinced that

04:43.063 --> 04:58.418
probably, unless we can deal effectively with 
that, and I don't think we can, that we probably

04:43.063 --> 04:58.418
shouldn't be using fission as a major source of 
heat. a power in the future, and it's too bad

04:59.090 --> 05:02.495
because it's so attractive otherwise. I think 
they can deal effectively with the waste. That's

05:07.122 --> 05:07.963
not my concern. My concern is that they are going to 
have some bad accidents and that those accidents

05:08.024 --> 05:16.977
are going to do a lot of harm to a lot of people. So I'm 
not sure it's worth the gamble. Are you optimistic

05:20.563 --> 05:26.291
about the ocean as a producer of food, as an 
oceanographer? Oh, I think so. I think

05:28.790 --> 05:50.572
my view is that now we're about the same point that 
the

05:28.790 --> 05:50.572
country was in 1860 when

05:28.790 --> 05:50.572
we were hunting buffalo. If we had continued to 
improve our ability to hunt buffalo, they would

05:51.713 --> 05:57.379
have disappeared even faster. Instead, we learn 
how to farm and to husband cows and to actually feed

05:57.697 --> 06:11.636
them and collect them together, essentially the 
farming effort that's going on. And I think once we

06:11.696 --> 06:25.915
stop worrying about improving our ability to 
catch fish, start worrying more about how to farm

06:11.696 --> 06:25.915
the seeds, that the seeds can really, you know, 
they can, I think the potential for, supplying

06:26.620 --> 06:42.239
proteins is

06:26.620 --> 06:42.239
certainly not unlimited, but it certainly goes 
orders of magnitude over above what we're talking

06:26.620 --> 06:42.239
about now in the sustained yield of the oceans in 
the natural conditions. Third comment, then, on

06:43.180 --> 06:48.467
these fields you've defined as pressing fields, I 
suppose. How successful will we be in mining the

06:48.487 --> 06:56.256
ocean, producing finite resources from the 
ocean, at a cost which is within some kind of a

06:56.877 --> 07:02.843
bottom line in terms of cost.

07:05.846 --> 07:26.547
Well, I'm certainly not an expert, but I was 
exposed to a rather thorough briefing by

07:05.846 --> 07:26.547
Marquis Sunnyvale, where their manganese nodule 
effort and the Glomar Explorer effort were

07:05.846 --> 07:26.547
housed. This was before the explorer went out and 
picked up a piece of a submarine. But they went

07:32.631 --> 07:46.887
through the whole exercise for, this was at a COA 
meeting out at Stanford, went through the whole

07:32.631 --> 07:46.887
exercise of how they examined, how they decided 
whether or not to go into a field like this. And

07:47.407 --> 07:51.572
their first step was to do a complete market study 
on on present-day mining, on the grades of ores

07:51.974 --> 08:06.094
that are being used to recover copper and other 
minerals, the potential for finding more of

07:51.974 --> 08:06.094
those, the whole market study bit. And they 
decided that the

08:07.175 --> 08:21.255
copper concentrations, for example, in 
manganese nodules, is now better, higher, around

08:07.175 --> 08:21.255
2%. than the copper concentrations in the ores of 
the mines that they're now mining. And therefore,

08:28.112 --> 08:31.796
they said, then it's worth looking into. And then 
they identified all the engineering problems

08:31.856 --> 08:37.462
associated with doing that kind of mining. The 
first study was a million dollar operation. Then

08:42.487 --> 08:49.555
that engineering study was a $10 million 
operation, identifying all the engineering

08:42.487 --> 08:49.555
problems. And they, at that time, were in the third 
step, which costs about $100 million. And that is

08:53.992 --> 08:59.700
tackling the remaining engineering problems. 
What kind of a nozzle do you use to pull them up? Do

09:02.003 --> 09:07.311
you use airlift or dredge or what? And they felt 
that they had essentially solved the major

09:07.331 --> 09:16.825
engineering problems with recovering it from the 
ocean.

09:17.193 --> 09:29.449
The fourth step, which had cost a billion dollars, 
and that is to actually start mining and

09:17.193 --> 09:29.449
recovering the metals from it and marketing them, 
was the one they were about to launch into. And

09:29.609 --> 09:45.951
that's the step at which they felt they had to have 
some assurance, either from the federal

09:29.609 --> 09:45.951
government on how the US government was going to 
protect their interests at sea, or some

09:29.609 --> 09:45.951
international agreement on how they'd operate at 
sea. And, you know, the Japanese are in it, and the

09:46.572 --> 09:51.740
Germans are in it, and the French are in it, and the 
U.S. is in it. And I would guess that within no more

09:53.102 --> 10:03.977
than 20 years, maybe 10, we'll be recovering 
medals from the bottom of the sea. I think once we

10:04.919 --> 10:07.022
start, it's going to get easier. Yeah, but that 
anticipates another question of mine, and that

10:07.042 --> 10:11.989
is, How are you going to use the sea and utilize the 
sea? And how is the foundation going to encourage

10:16.230 --> 10:26.561
projects when it becomes fairly apparent with 
200-mile boundaries, international

10:16.230 --> 10:26.561
agreements, that oceanographers' activities 
will be more and more limited?

10:31.766 --> 10:32.407
Well, I'm not... I think it's going to be more 
