16:07.157 --> 16:12.102
Now, while you were involved both in your own 
research and as a member of a funding agency, what

16:12.335 --> 16:24.449
program did you feel to be the most successful, and 
what program did you feel to be the most disastrous

16:12.335 --> 16:24.449
fate?

16:24.469 --> 16:26.712
Depends on what you mean, project? Project, 
right, or a project that was to lead to a series of

16:26.772 --> 16:40.047
projects, either

16:26.772 --> 16:40.047
way. Well, I think I had a strong hand at ONR for a 
number of years in developing deep-sea

16:42.625 --> 16:52.537
telemetering buoys. And I thought that's going to 
be absolutely necessary. It's the wave of the

16:57.223 --> 16:58.825
future. We'd better get it developed and get to 
using it.

17:06.487 --> 17:08.269
And I thought I had done everything right. I had set 
up a committee of scientists to advise on the

17:08.289 --> 17:20.442
development of this hardware all the way along so 
that when it was ready, we could just hand it to them

17:08.289 --> 17:20.442
and they'd take it away and use it, and the whole 
bit. And in the end, it turned out that the tool was

17:22.304 --> 17:36.038
so expensive and so unreliable, even after 
putting $10 or $12 million in it, whatever it was,

17:36.828 --> 17:39.111
that it just wasn't suitable as an oceanographic 
tool. And I consider that to be pretty much of a

17:39.872 --> 17:50.067
disaster for which I had a great deal of 
responsibility, if not the whole

17:39.872 --> 17:50.067
responsibility. And I feel bad about it. I just had 
no idea of how much the things would cost in the end

17:54.573 --> 18:04.287
or how difficult it would be to develop a system 
that you could put in the ocean and leave for a year.

18:04.756 --> 18:09.182
without having something go wrong with some piece 
of it that would essentially inactivate the whole

18:04.756 --> 18:09.182
thing. And we spent a lot of money using space 
technology on it, the whole industrial weight of

18:10.404 --> 18:24.884
general dynamics, and failure modes, and 
reliability. And you get all through, you still

18:24.964 --> 18:28.429
don't have a workable tool. And you don't have one 
that

18:35.047 --> 18:39.132
that the community can afford to buy very many of 
them. And so now I've given up developing systems

18:39.152 --> 18:44.237
for oceanographers. When they come in and say, we 
want this system for this research task, then

18:44.558 --> 18:51.786
we'll try and get the system for them. But I've 
given up trying to anticipate what I think they're

18:51.826 --> 18:55.931
going to need.

18:58.934 --> 19:01.577
That's probably one of the biggest failures. The 
most successful program that I've been

19:02.941 --> 19:09.790
associated, had anything to do with, and I haven't 
had too much to do with, is the Climap program. And

19:10.971 --> 19:14.095
this is the, it's an IDOE project. Essentially 
it's a project which the paleontologists who

19:16.298 --> 19:31.277
study fossil fuel, fossil in the deep sea 
sediments, try to say something about the age of

19:16.298 --> 19:31.277
the sediments or when the conditions changed by 
looking at these fossils in the deep sea core. And

19:42.210 --> 19:51.502
up until we supported the Climap program, each 
paleontologist was very excited about his own

19:42.210 --> 19:51.502
work. And he would show you micro photographs of 
forams until you could, you know, you were sick of

19:51.542 --> 19:55.406
them. But there wasn't any, outside of telling 
you, outside of telling the oil companies

19:55.426 --> 20:02.395
whether, what geologic age, was being examined in 
the cores. It didn't tell you an awful lot. But the

20:07.620 --> 20:24.357
scientists at Brown, John Embry, at Lamont, Jim 
Hayes,

20:07.620 --> 20:24.357
at Oregon State University, Ted Moore, put 
together a program with about 25 to 30

20:07.620 --> 20:24.357
paleontologists. And they welded them into a team 
so that they had

20:32.800 --> 20:49.602
each one working on the same core, each one 
obtaining a different bit of evidence on that

20:32.800 --> 20:49.602
core, so that when you put all this evidence 
together and did some statistical manipulation

20:32.800 --> 20:49.602
with it, you could say what the ocean temperature 
was at that time, at that place, at the surface. And

20:51.044 --> 20:57.833
they developed a map of the Ice Age Ocean 18,000 
years ago. They induced the global atmospheric

21:02.365 --> 21:15.179
modelers to use that data, that picture of the 
global ocean, to examine their own models and the

21:02.365 --> 21:15.179
constants that the modelers were using. Just a 
very, very successful program.

