22:03.807 --> 22:17.725
oceanography is just the application of that 
science to the oceans. So if you get an

22:18.406 --> 22:30.642
undergraduate degree in oceanography, you don't 
have any strength in any particular field, not

22:18.406 --> 22:30.642
physics, not mathematics, or anything else, and 
you really end up more at a technician role than you

22:31.313 --> 22:35.559
do at a researcher role. And some of the most 
successful people have gone on and got their PhDs

22:36.281 --> 22:50.182
in the hard science, in chemistry or in physics, 
and then come into oceanography as a matter of

22:36.281 --> 22:50.182
interest. And in fact, that's where they all came 
from initially. And that's still where many of the

22:54.268 --> 22:58.034
good ones come from. But oceanography is 
training. their own experts now, very

23:01.638 --> 23:06.586
successfully, they can compete with. Monk came in 
that way, and Stommel came in that way. All of the

23:10.271 --> 23:19.726
older group of people, it's the only way they could 
get in, as a matter of fact. But I would certainly, I

23:19.746 --> 23:29.721
think,

23:19.746 --> 23:29.721
if you want to say I'd like to work in the field at the 
technical level, at the technician level, then

23:30.157 --> 23:31.699
you get an undergraduate degree. But if you really 
want to do research, your own research, an

23:31.959 --> 23:41.150
advanced way forward, you really have to have an 
undergraduate degree in a basic science. Which

23:41.171 --> 23:47.558
oceanographer possibly had the greatest 
influence on directing your career? On my career?

23:50.061 --> 23:50.562
Your career.

